t academic work has focused on how the majority Sunni Muslims conclude marriages. This volume, in contrast, focuses on Twelver Shi'a Muslims in Iran, Pakistan, Oman, Indonesia, Norway, and the Netherlands. The volume makes an original contribution to understanding the global dynamics of Shi'a marriage practices in a wide range of contexts--not only its geographical spread but also by providing a critical analysis of the socio-economic, religious, ethnic, and political discourses of each context. The book sheds light on new marriage forms presented through a bottom up approach focusing on the lived experiences of Shi'a Muslims negotiating a diverse range of relationships and forms of belonging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamic marriage customs and rites. 0aShiitesxMarriage customs and rites. 0aShīʻahxCustoms and practices. 0aShīʻahxDoctrines. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  areligion, gender, Sh'ia, Sh'ia Muslim, Islam, Muslim marriage, Muslim minority, Sunni Muslims, Iran, Pakistan, Oman, Indonesia, Norway, the Netherlands, marriage practices, Muslim practices, middle east, middle east studies, Muslim culture, tradition, marriage, dating, Muslim dating, Shia marriage, temporary marriage.1 aAsgarilaleh, Tara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerta, Péter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBøe, Marianne Hafnor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirard, Sophie Yvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirard, Sophie-Yvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHafnor, Marianne Bøe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHegland, Mary Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1